05801nam a22007815i 9780271095868DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710958687 a10.1515/97802710958682doi  a(DE-B1597)679901  a(OCoLC)1416922846  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aN5961 7aART0150702bisacsh04a709.02223/eng/2024011800aOut of Bounds :bExploring the Limits of Medieval Art /ced. by Maria Alessia Rossi, Pamela A. Patton. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSigna: Papers of the Index of Medieval Art at Princeton University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Shifting Boundaries: Medieval Art History for Now -- t2. On Account of the Rotundity of the Earth: Steps Toward an Inclusive Medieval Art -- t3. Medieval Masks? Meditations on Method Out of Bounds -- t4. Along the Art-Historical Margins of the Medieval Mediterranean -- t5. Looking at the “Center” from the “Border”: An Exchange of Franco- Ottoman Gifts and the Perception of Art Around 1400 -- t6. Alexander the Great’s Encounters with the Sacred in Medieval History Writing: From the Shahnameh to the Histoire ancienne jusqu’à César -- t7. Fashioning the Gendered, Classed, and White Self: A Sephardi Cultural Project -- t8. Beyond Traditional Boundaries: Medieval Art and Architecture in Eastern Europe -- t9. “The Summit of the Earth”: What Armenian Texts Can Do for the History of Medieval Art and Beyond -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhere are the limits of medieval art as a field of study? What happens when conventionally trained art historians disregard the chronological, geographical, or cultural parameters that both direct and protect their scholarship? Beginning with Thelma K. Thomas and Alicia Walker’s acute assessment of the need for a “medieval art history for now,” the essays in Out of Bounds ask what happens when the study of medieval art disregards boundaries that it once obeyed. The volume focuses on questions surrounding the production of knowledge and on how scholarly investigation beyond the conventional thematic boundaries of medieval art history is changing, demonstrating how the field can address the ethics of scholarship today by positing a global turn in response to growing demands for socially responsible medieval studies. Collectively, the contributors demonstrate how “going out of bounds” can transform modern understanding of the people, traditions, and relationships that gave rise to medieval works. As such, this book argues for the necessity of reshaping scholarly discourse about the nature and significance of medieval art and generates fresh scholarly interpretations and important new critical tools for teaching and researching the Middle Ages.The contributors to this volume are Suzanne Conklin Akbari, Michele Bacci, Jill Caskey, Eva Frojmovic, Sarah M. Guérin, Christina Maranci, Alice Isabella Sullivan, Thelma K. Thomas, Michele Tomasi, and Alicia Walker.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, MedievalvCongresses. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAfrican masks.  aArmenian texts.  aFranco-Ottoman gift exchange.  aIndex of Medieval Art.  aMiddle Ages.  aart historians.  aglobal studies.  aglobal turn.  aiconography.  amedieval art.  apostmedieval.  asocially responsible medieval studies.  atransculturalism.1 aBacci, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaskey, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConklin Akbari, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel